Youth should take up new roles and become change agents. This is the only way to build a better Kenya as they will meaningfully participate in nation building- as solution providers to all the societal needs.
In his address to The Youth Congress Youth Leagues recently, former Chief Justice Willy Mutunga aptly put it when he said that for youth to fundamentally change Kenya, they have first to accept that the crisis facing us is that of poor political leadership — enslaved by foreign interests.  It has been easy in recent years for political players to target youth in their manifestos seeking votes, but since they are not properly organised as a distinct political unit, promises are trashed after those they support ascend to power.





With 80 per cent of the country’s population below 35 years, and the latest information technology having penetrated well among the youth than the rest of the society, organising themselves along their shared experiences, needs, concerns and aspirations is not a far-fetched dream.
Multiparty politics
A distinct political unit that can pronounce itself on ideals of good governance, condemning vices such as corruption, tribalism, politics of division, greed, enslavement by foreign interests and injustices, would be a good starting point. Youth should envision contesting for political power.



