Defining a new platform in which Kenyans can be socialised into politics will diminish the highly divisive ethnic politics that have defined Kenya since 1991, when we ushered in multiparty politics. It will also lay the foundation on which others such as women and labour unions can as well shape politics by bargaining inclusion.
It is impressive to see how the young people have taken the lead in other areas. They are the drivers of the private sector economy through highly advanced technologies and systems, which can be replicated with great success if applied in politics.
It is also inspiring to see many young people at the community level stand for human rights and social justices. We also have young people in civil society, in Parliament, and in places of worship. These youth leadership roles can provide beacons to open up more leadership spaces.
As we approach the General Election, young people should exercise their rights not only to vote, but to lead. Most important, youth should run for electoral office and provide alternative political leadership that the country needs. If young people are not too young to vote, they are not too young to lead.
